In the last decade, alternatives to ACV for herpesvirus treatment have emerged and become commercially available as therapeutic drugs. Ganciclovir is a nucleic acid analog that does not require viral proteins for its activation in the cell (i.e., viral TK) (
 Markham and Faulds, 1994; 
 Prichard et al., 2011; 
 Vere Hodge and Field, 2013; 
 Poole and James, 2018). These compounds differ from each other either, in their molecular processing into an active form of an acyclic guanosine analog, or bioavailability which significantly determines the frequency of administration (
 De Clercq, 2013).
